05057nam a22007215i 9781442694200DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426942007 a10.3138/97814426942002doi  a(DE-B1597)618920  a(OCoLC)1268529507  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a973.9240922231 aPrice, James R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpiritualizing Politics without Politicizing Religion :bThe Example of Sargent Shriver /cJames R. Price, Kenneth R. Melchin. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tChapter One. Religion and Politics: Doing Things Differently -- tChapter Two. The Public Faith of Sargent Shriver, 1955–1959 -- tChapter Three. Shriver on Spirituality and Politics, 1961–1964 -- tChapter Four. Explaining What Shriver Did -- tChapter Five. Religion, Politics, and the Peace Corps -- tChapter Six. The Way Forward -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe clash of religion and politics has been a steady source of polarization in North America. In order to think wisely and constructively about the spiritual dimension of our political life, there is need for an approach that can both maintain the diversity of belief and foster values founded on the principles of religion. In Spiritualizing Politics without Politicizing Religion, James R. Price and Kenneth R. Melchin provide a possible framework, approaching issues in politics via a profile of Sargent Shriver (1915-2011), an American diplomat, politician, and a driving force behind the creation of the Peace Corps. Focusing on the speeches Shriver delivered in the course of his work to advance civil rights and build world peace, Price and Melchin highlight the spiritual component of his efforts to improve institutional structures and solve social problems. They contextualize Shriver’s approach by contrasting it with contemporary, landmark decisions of the U.S Supreme Court on the role of religion in politics. In doing so, Spiritualizing Politics without Politicizing Religion explains that navigating the relationship of religion and politics requires attending to both the religious diversity that politics must guard and the religious involvements that politics needs to do its work.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmbassadorszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPoliticianszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aReligion and politicszUnited States. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aBernard Longergan.  aPeace Corps.  aSargent Shriver.  apolitical life.  areligion in politics.  aspiritual politics.1 aMelchin, Kenneth R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311127214608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076715540uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144269420040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442694200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781442694200/original  a978-3-11-076715-5  Univers